1
00:00:00,110 --> 00:00:04,010
In this video we are going to learn back end for front end pattern.

2
00:00:05,020 --> 00:00:11,620
Backend for frontend pattern basically separates API gateways as per the specific frontend application.

3
00:00:12,100 --> 00:00:18,070
In current design we have several backend services which are consumed by the front end applications,

4
00:00:18,070 --> 00:00:24,040
and between them we put API gateway for handling the routing and aggregate operations.

5
00:00:24,190 --> 00:00:26,950
But this makes a single point of failure.

6
00:00:27,130 --> 00:00:34,240
So in order to solve this problem, backend for frontend offers to create several API gateways and grouping

7
00:00:34,240 --> 00:00:39,550
them the client applications according to their boundaries and split them different API gateways.

8
00:00:41,220 --> 00:00:47,190
A single and complex API gateway can be risky and becoming a bottleneck into your architecture.

9
00:00:47,550 --> 00:00:55,380
Larger systems often expose multiple API gateways by grouping client type like mobile, web, and desktop

10
00:00:55,380 --> 00:00:56,370
functionality.

11
00:00:56,460 --> 00:01:02,970
Back end for front end pattern is useful when you want to avoid customizing a single backend for multiple

12
00:01:02,970 --> 00:01:03,930
interfaces.

13
00:01:04,980 --> 00:01:09,600
So we should create several API gateways as per user interfaces.

14
00:01:09,630 --> 00:01:16,620
These API gateways provide to best match the needs of the front end environment, without worrying about

15
00:01:16,620 --> 00:01:19,020
the affecting other front end applications.

16
00:01:19,020 --> 00:01:24,270
The back end for front end pattern provides directions for implementing multiple gateways.

17
00:01:24,870 --> 00:01:30,450
The main purpose of using back end for front end pattern is to provide client applications.

18
00:01:30,450 --> 00:01:34,650
Has a focused interface that connects with the internal microservices.

19
00:01:34,650 --> 00:01:41,220
For example, data consumption by a mobile user interface could be different from data consumption by

20
00:01:41,220 --> 00:01:42,240
a web browser.

21
00:01:42,510 --> 00:01:49,920
In that case, for better data representation, two backend for front end pattern can be used one for

22
00:01:49,920 --> 00:01:51,570
the web, one for the mobile.

23
00:01:53,420 --> 00:01:59,180
Let's have a look at the image on the slide with using multiple backend for front end API gateways.

24
00:01:59,210 --> 00:02:06,410
There are three API gateways one for the web, one for the mobile and another for the desktop applications.

25
00:02:06,410 --> 00:02:12,890
So with following backend for front end pattern, we have created three API gateways that can provide

26
00:02:12,890 --> 00:02:17,000
a different APIs tailored for each client application type.

